Review: Iteration with for loops

Last time, we showed how to use for loops to repeat ourselves.

mean(rnorm(1))
## [1] -1.00747
mean(rnorm(2))
## [1] 0.9752125
mean(rnorm(3))
## [1] 0.05401295

Review: Iteration with for loops

Becomes:

sample_sizes <- 1:30
means <- numeric(length(sample_sizes))

for (i in seq_along(sample_sizes)) {
  means[i] = mean(rnorm(i))
}

Another way to repeat ourselves: functions!

R is a functional programming language, so we largely prefer functions as the way to do things.

calculate_sample_mean <- function(sample_size) {
  sample_mean <- mean(rnorm(sample_size))
  
  sample_mean
}

calculate_sample_mean(1)
## [1] -2.11974

Lets break it down

Functions

The general structure of a function is as follows:

function_name <- function(arguments) {
  do_this(arguments)
}

Functions

There are three main parts to a function:

  1. Function name
  2. Function arguments
  3. Function body
function_name <- function(arguments) {
  do_this(arguments)
}

Simple example: printing output

print("Number 1!")
## [1] "Number 1!"
print("Number 2!")
## [1] "Number 2!"
print("Number 3!")
## [1] "Number 3!"
# and so on...
print("Number 10!")
## [1] "Number 10!"

Simple example: printing output

Set up the body of the function:

name <- function() {
  
}

You can do this with a code snippet in RStudio (start typing “fun”, then press Tab!)

Simple example: printing output

Come up with a short, descriptive name:

shout_number <- function() {
  
}

We recommend verb_thing(), so calculate_size() or compare_prices() as vs. fun1(), calc().

Simple example: printing output

Decide what the input to the function will be:

shout_number <- function(number) {
  
}

Simple example: printing output

Do something to that input:

shout_number <- function(number) {
  paste0("Number ", number, "!")
}

Note that we dont need to explicitly call return() - the last line of the code will be the value returned by the function.

Simple example: printing output

Test it out:

shout_number <- function(number) {
  paste0("Number ", number, "!")
}

shout_number(1)
## [1] "Number 1!"

Question: does number exist in my R environment after I run this function? Why or why not?

Second example: calculating the mean of a sample

calculate_sample_mean <- function(sample_size) {
  sample_mean <- mean(rnorm(sample_size))
  
  sample_mean
}

calculate_sample_mean(1)
## [1] 0.6266243

Function defaults

We can set values to be defaults, but the user can change them.

Our function from before:

calculate_sample_mean <- function(sample_size) {
  sample_mean <- mean(rnorm(sample_size))
  
  sample_mean
}

Function defaults

We can set values to be defaults, but the user can change them.

We add more arguments, and set default values for them:

calculate_sample_mean <- function(sample_size, 
                                  our_mean = 0, 
                                  our_sd = 1) {
  sample_mean <- mean(rnorm(sample_size, 
                            mean = our_mean, 
                            sd = our_sd))
  
  sample_mean
}

Function defaults

calculate_sample_mean(10, our_mean = 6, our_sd = 2)
## [1] 5.61366
calculate_sample_mean(our_sd = 2, sample_size = 9)
## [1] 0.7786749

This wont work:

calculate_sample_mean(our_mean = 5)
Error in rnorm(sample_size, mean = our_mean, sd = our_sd) : 
  argument "sample_size" is missing, with no default

Functions in functions

We can pass functions as arguments to other functions. Before:

calculate_sample_mean <- function(sample_size, 
                                  our_mean = 0, 
                                  our_sd = 1) {
  sample_mean <- mean(rnorm(sample_size, 
                            mean = our_mean, 
                            sd = our_sd))
  
  sample_mean
}

Functions in functions

We can pass functions as arguments to other functions. After:

summarize_sample <- function(sample_size, 
                                  our_mean = 0, 
                                  our_sd = 1,
                                  summary_fxn = mean) {
  summary_stat <- summary_fxn(rnorm(sample_size, 
                            mean = our_mean, 
                            sd = our_sd))
  
  summary_stat
}

Functions in functions

calculate_sample_mean(sample_size = 10, 
                      our_mean = 0, 
                      our_sd = 1)
## [1] 0.4277807
summarize_sample(sample_size = 10, 
                our_mean = 0, 
                our_sd = 1, 
                summary_fxn = max)
## [1] 1.301701

calculate_sample_mean() is now probably the wrong name for this function - we should call it summarize_sample() or something like that.

Detour: probability distributions

R has built-in functions for working with distributions.

example what it does?
d dnorm(x) returns pdf value at x
p pnorm(x) returns CDF value at x
q qnorm(q) returns inverse CDF for a given quantile
r rnorm(n) generates a random sample of size n

Probability distributions you are familiar with are likely built-in to R.

For example, the binomial distribution has dbinom(), pbinom(), qbinom(), rbinom(). The t distribution has dt(), pt(), qt(), rt(), etc.

Read this tutorial for more information.

Best practices for functions

  1. Keep your functions simple and short
  2. Name functions well (verb_thing() is generally good), and document what they take as input and output
  3. Check and debug your functions as you write them, not at the very end

Appendix: map() family of functions

Functions are powerful when map()ed to lists:

shout_number <- function(number) {
  paste0("Number ", number, "!")
}
numbers <- 1:10

# map returns a list the same length as numbers.
map(numbers, shout_number)

map() family of functions

The infixes influence the type of thing that is output:

numbers <- 1:10

map_chr(numbers, shout_number)
##  [1] "Number 1!"  "Number 2!"  "Number 3!"  "Number 4!"  "Number 5!" 
##  [6] "Number 6!"  "Number 7!"  "Number 8!"  "Number 9!"  "Number 10!"
